{"cursor":"15577","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n'Substance theory', or 'substance attribute theory', is an ontological theory\nabout objecthood, positing that a substance is a distinct thing-in-itself, independent from any accidental property it may bear.\n\nSubstance is a key concept in ontology and metaphysics, which may be classified\ninto monist, dualist or pluralist varieties according to how many substances or\nindividuals are said to populate, furnish or exist in the world. According to\nMonistic views, such as those of stoicism and Spinoza, there is only one\nsubstance, pneuma or God, respectively. These modes of thinking are sometimes\nassociated with the idea of immanence. Dualism sees the world as being composed\nof two fundamental substances, for example, the Cartesian substance dualism of\nmind and matter. Pluralist philosophies include Plato's Theory of Forms and\nAristotle's hylomorphic categories.\n","linknr":493,"url":"Substance_theory","recorded":1362689040,"links":52,"instances":["philosophy","dialogue","philosophy","philosophy","philosophy","stoic","philosophy_and_religion","encyclical","philosophy","philosophy","philosophy","philosophy"],"pdf":["http://www20.uludag.edu.tr/~kadir/Roma.pdf","http://www20.uludag.edu.tr/~kadir/Roma.pdf"],"categories":["Ontology","Aristotelianism","Metaphysical theories"],"headings":["Ancient Greek philosophy","Early Western philosophy","Criticisms of the concept of substance","Irreducible concepts","Arguments supporting the theory","Bundle theory","Stoicism","See also","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a4/Aristoteles_Louvre.jpg/100px-Aristoteles_Louvre.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cf/Socrates_blue_version2.png/20px-Socrates_blue_version2.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/0/c/c/0cc175b9c0f1b6a831c399e269772661.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/9/2/e/92eb5ffee6ae2fec3ad71c777531578f.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/mat